{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 14:06:10.258568", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nGoal: assess current network health, detect anomalies, localize faulty device(s), and identify likely root cause(s). No mitigation steps provided — only findings and evidence.\n\nExecutive summary\n- The network shows signs of an OSPF adjacency/LSDB synchronization problem among the core routers (particularly between router_core_2 and router_core_3). This produced transient or partial reachability failures from access hosts to the server/DNS subnet (10.200.0.0/24) in initial automated reachability checks.\n- Server-side connectivity (web servers and DNS) and server-access switch are healthy and can reach each other and the access hosts in manual tests. The issue appears to be OSPF LSA propagation / adjacency instability in the core rather than a failure of the servers or access switches.\n- Devices implicated: router_core_3 (primary), router_core_2 (secondary). Evidence shows at least one adjacency in a non-fully-synchronized state (Loading) and missing/unsynchronized summary LSAs on some routers during checks.\n\nDetailed observations and evidence\n\n1) Baseline reachability scan (automated)\n- Initial reachability snapshot (get_reachability) showed multiple critical failures:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): 4/4 lost (100%).\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> dns_server and all web_server_0..3: 100% loss (where tested).\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> host_2_1_1_1: 100% loss.\n- At the same time, web servers and dns_server had full intra-server connectivity (web_server_X <-> dns_server and web_server_X <-> web_server_Y all OK). This points to a problem in connectivity from the access networks to the server network (or a control-plane inconsistency), rather than a server-side problem.\n\n2) Host and switch interface state (get_host_net_config)\n- host_1_1_1_1: eth0 = 10.1.1.2/24, default via 10.1.1.1\n- host_2_1_1_1: eth0 = 10.2.1.219/24, default via 10.2.1.1\n- switch_di