acency is not fully synchronized and the router is still requesting LSAs.\n  - Several neighbors are showing \"Full/DR\" and \"Full/Backup\" roles on what are expected to be point-to-point links (DR/BDR roles are typically seen on multi-access networks). The presence of DR/BDR on these backbone links is unexpected and indicates either:\n    - OSPF network type is treated as broadcast on links that are effectively point-to-point (or)\n    - The topology or FRR interface configuration results in virtual multi-access behavior.\n- router_core_3's OSPF database (show ip ospf database) summary LSAs include:\n  - 10.1.1.0/24 (advertised by 172.16.0.0)\n  - 10.2.1.0/24 (advertised by 172.16.0.1)\n  - and some /31s\n  Notably, the 10.200.0.0/24 (server subnet) is not present in the summary LSAs on router_core_3's database snapshot. (switch_server_access does show 10.200.0.0/24 connected in its routing table.)\n\n6) OSPF DB synchronization indicators\n- router_core_3's neighbor state of \"Loading/Backup\" and non-zero DB request counters in some neighbor outputs indicate LSAs were still being requested and the LSDB was not fully consistent at the time of capture.\n- This is consistent with the reachability scan behavior (initial failures) followed by successful manual pings (subsequent convergence or partial recovery).\n\nLocalization of the fault\n- Primary suspected device: router_core_3\n  - Evidence: router_core_3 shows a neighbor in Loading/Backup (172.16.0.1 — router_core_2), and its OSPF database snapshot lacks the 10.200.0.0/24 summary LSA (advertised by switch_server_access). This suggests LSAs from the server area were not fully propagated/installed on core_3 at that time.\n- Secondary suspected device: router_core_2\n  - Evidence: asymmetry in the neighbor state for the link between core_2 and core_3: router_core_2's neighbor list shows the adjacency as Full/DR while router_core_3 shows Loading/Backup toward router_core_2 — inconsistent adjacency states between the