/ transient: the automated reachability run captured a period of failure (hosts could not reach servers), while manual spot tests thereafter showed successful connectivity. This pattern is consistent with an OSPF synchronization/convergence event that was in progress or unstable at the time of the scan.\n- Confidence:\n  - High confidence that OSPF adjacency/LSDB synchronization issues exist (evidence: Loading neighbor, DB requests, missing summary LSAs).\n  - Moderate-to-high confidence that core router adjacency between router_core_2 and router_core_3 is the main locus of the problem.\n  - Moderate confidence that this explains the transient reachability failures to the server subnet during the observed period.\n\nRelevant data excerpts (key evidence)\n- Initial reachability: host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server: 100% loss; host_2_1_1_1 -> web_server_0..3: 100% loss.\n- OSPF neighbor (router_core_3): shows neighbor 172.16.0.1 in Loading/Backup state (DB requests pending).\n- OSPF database (router_core_3): summary LSAs shown include 10.1.1.0 and 10.2.1.0, but not 10.200.0.0/24.\n- Direct ping tests (later): host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2 (dns_server): 4/4 OK (avg ~3.9 ms), showing connectivity once DB was synchronized or during a healthy interval.\n\nRecommended next diagnostic data to collect (if further analysis is desired)\n- Show full OSPF LSDB on all core routers (router_core_1/2/3) concurrently to compare presence/absence and age/sequence numbers of the 10.200.0.0/24 summary LSA (I did obtain router_core_3 DB; comparing all three would confirm propagation gaps).\n- Show interface OSPF network type and related FRR interface configs on the core links to confirm whether links are configured as point-to-point or broadcast (to validate DR/BDR anomalies).\n- Show \"show ip ospf interface\" on core routers to get timers, network type, and whether any retransmissions or MTU mismatches are flagged.\n- Capture OSPF debug/log around the time of the automated reachability test to see LSA flooding/retransmit behavior and any errors.\n- Repeat a full reachability scan while simultaneously streaming OSPF neighbor/table outputs to capture correlation between route availability and packet loss.\n\nConclusion\n- The primary abnormality is OSPF adjacency/LSDB synchronization instability among the core routers (router_core_2 and router_core_3), resulting in transient loss of route visibility to the server subnet (10.200.0.0/24) from parts of the access network at the time of the automated scan. The server farm and server-access switch themselves appear healthy. The immediate focus for further diagnosis should be OSPF adjacency behavior and interface/network-type configuration on the core backbone links to confirm the root cause.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 21085, "output_tokens": 5179, "total_tokens": 26264, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 20224}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2432}}}
